In this phase of the lab, the core network services were installed and configured on Windows Server to simulate a small enterprise environment.

The following roles were deployed using the Add Roles and Features Wizard: Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS), DNS Server, and DHCP Server.

The server was then promoted to a Domain Controller by creating a new Active Directory forest and defining a domain name for the lab environment. During this process, a Directory Services Restore Mode (DSRM) password was configured to allow recovery and maintenance operations if needed.

After the domain controller was configured, the DNS service was automatically integrated with Active Directory to provide name resolution within the domain. A forward lookup zone was created for the domain to allow systems to locate network resources.

Finally, the DHCP server was configured with a scope that automatically assigns IP addresses and network configuration settings to client machines. This allows devices in the lab network to receive IP addresses, gateway information, and DNS settings dynamically.

These services form the foundation of the lab infrastructure and enable centralized authentication, network management, and communication between systems in the environment.
